During the voyage, Zevallos was anxiously devising methods to tranquillize Paraguay, which he imagined to be embroiled with intes- tine war, and devoted to King Nicholas. On coming in sight of the shores of Buenos-AyreS‚ lest by a sudden landing he should endanger his men, he despatched some soldiers in a boat to feel the way before them. Perceiving a multi- tude assembled on the bank of the river plata, they hailed them from afar with the usual inter- rogation of the Spanish guardS‚ Quiete vive?- Who reigns here? With one voice they ex- claimed, that Ferdinand the Sixth was their king, and should remain so as long as they lived. This was more than enough to quiet the fears of the soldiers, who, deceived by European reports, imagined that King Nicholas would be dethroned with the utmost difficulty, and at the expense of their own and much foreign blood.
